   "source": [
    "# OpenGL Compute Shaders: SPA\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook is the third in a series of notebooks about general-purpose GPU (GPGPU) computing using OpenGLâ€™s compute shaders with the goal of an accurate and fast GPU implementation of Reda & Andreas's Solar Position Algorithm.  There's still some work to do, but what I have is already useful in many contexts and as I get close to the finish line I wanted to do some more rigorous validation in terms of accuracy and runtime speed, using pvlib's numpy and numba implementations as the baseline.\n",
    "\n",
    "These comparisons (both error and runtime) will be specific to this particular GPU.  I will be interested to see how the results vary across devices..."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "23e87e84-f364-45a4-9eb7-ba6ab3359544",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import moderngl\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import pvlib\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c5e62d19-3afa-4ba3-9503-ca391841ffcd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This function does the data processing needed to shuffle the arguments to and from the OpenGL kernel, as well as coordinate the kernel execution itself.  Again, no promises that this is the best way to do it -- but it works!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "e970a6f3-fc67-4a3b-bd37-732819003d8a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "context = moderngl.create_standalone_context(require=430)\n",
    "\n",
    "def gpu_spa(times, lat, lon, elevation=0, temperature=12, pressure=101325, delta_t=67, atmos_refract=0.5667, groupsize=1024):\n",
    "    n_times = len(times)\n",
    "    n_vars = 5\n",
    "    unixtimes = np.array(times.view(np.int64)/10**9, dtype=np.uint32)\n",
    "    params = np.array([lat, lon, elevation, temperature, pressure, delta_t, atmos_refract], dtype='f4')\n",
    "\n",
    "    with open(\"spa.glsl\", \"r\") as f:\n",
    "        source = f.read().replace(\"%%N%%\", str(min(n_times, groupsize)))\n",
    "\n",
    "    compute_shader = context.compute_shader(source)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    buffer_times = context.buffer(unixtimes)\n",
    "    buffer_parameters = context.buffer(params)\n",
    "    buffer_outputs = context.buffer(reserve=n_vars*4*n_times)\n",
    "\n",
    "    buffer_times.bind_to_storage_buffer(0)\n",
    "    buffer_parameters.bind_to_storage_buffer(1)\n",
    "    buffer_outputs.bind_to_storage_buffer(2)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    n_group = 1 + (n_times-1) // groupsize\n",
    "    compute_shader.run(group_x=n_group)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    outputs = np.frombuffer(buffer_outputs.read(), dtype=np.float32)\n",
    "    out = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "        'elevation': outputs[0::n_vars],\n",
    "        'apparent_elevation': outputs[1::n_vars],\n",
    "        'zenith': outputs[2::n_vars],\n",
    "        'apparent_zenith': outputs[3::n_vars],\n",
    "        'azimuth': outputs[4::n_vars],\n",
    "    }, index=times)\n",
    "    return out"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bc86e200-5803-46bc-bd34-6b00ee5349e3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Accuracy Benchmarks\n",
    "\n",
    "First, check that the GPU implementation gives the same output as pvlib under several test scenarios.  pvlib's numpy implementation is the reference."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "321a2b99-ca45-4416-a0ac-0661fece45b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2019 1-minute simulation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "30760693-04a9-4e1c-9ae1-2eef5fb96527",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def describe(x1, x2):\n",
    "    d = x1 - x2\n",
    "    return pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "        'rmse': (d**2).mean()**0.5,\n",
    "        'mbe': d.mean(),\n",
    "        'mae': d.abs().mean(),\n",
    "    }).T"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "e694bdad-0e29-4953-bcc1-137635e89cd7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "times = pd.date_range('2019-01-01', '2020-01-01', freq='T')\n",
    "gpu = gpu_spa(times, 40, -80)\n",
    "cpu = pvlib.solarposition.get_solarposition(times, 40, -80)"
   ]

   "id": "aaea4a77-a076-4138-aa62-b2c573cb4a41",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Error is very low for this test, although there is likely still some room for improvement.  These results (and all others in this notebook) are still using the `arcsin`/`arctan` hack from the previous post, so there is some accuracy to be gained there if nowhere else.\n",
    "\n",
    "One of SPA's claims to fame is its accuracy over such a wide time span; I'm not necessarily interested in trying to match that, but we should at least test some years besides 2019:"
   ]

   "source": [
    "Guess I need to take another look at my julian date handlers!  Moving on, let's try out different locations to make sure things don't get wonky at negative latitudes or near the poles or something:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "87a02930-de67-4d17-981d-475cfb31740d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Lat/Lon Sweep"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "1fb1e7db-8a85-4849-b76d-6075ccc9f726",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "times = pd.date_range('2019-01-01', '2020-01-01', freq='H')\n",
    "\n",
    "rmse = []\n",
    "mbe = []\n",
    "mae = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for lat in np.arange(-90, 90, 5):\n",
    "    for lon in np.arange(-180, 180, 10):\n",
    "        gpu = gpu_spa(times, lat, lon)\n",
    "        cpu = pvlib.solarposition.get_solarposition(times, lat, lon)\n",
    "        res = describe(cpu, gpu).assign(lat=lat, lon=lon)\n",
    "        rmse.append(res.loc['rmse', :])\n",
    "        mbe.append(res.loc['mbe', :])\n",
    "        mae.append(res.loc['mae', :])\n",
    "\n",
    "rmse = pd.concat(rmse, axis=1).T\n",
    "mbe = pd.concat(mbe, axis=1).T\n",
    "mae = pd.concat(mae, axis=1).T"
   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Some interesting patterns that I'm not immediately sure how to interpret, but in any case the variation with location doesn't seem very significant.  Now let's play with the other SPA knobs:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3ba7bfb6-4bad-4bd6-8e96-5ca4e66c3594",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Refraction Correction\n",
    "\n",
    "The SPA zenith refraction correction depends on annual average temperature and pressure.  To make sure that correction is calculated correctly, let's sweep across both and ensure that refraction-corrected (\"apparent\") zenith still matches between the two implementations.  The temperatures and pressures chosen here are each roughly representative of the ranges found on Earth, although certain combinations might not be particularly realistic."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "e0d311d6-7253-4f09-a14b-8e2df8a8e814",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 900x900 with 25 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "times = pd.date_range('2019-06-01', '2019-06-02', freq='10s')\n",
    "\n",
    "n = 5\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(n, n, sharex=True, sharey=True, dpi=75, figsize=(12, 12))\n",
    "\n",
    "for i, temperature in enumerate(np.linspace(-30, 30, num=n)):\n",
    "    for j, pressure in enumerate(np.linspace(30000, 102000, num=n)):\n",
    "        gpu = gpu_spa(times, 40, -80, pressure=pressure, temperature=temperature)\n",
    "        cpu = pvlib.solarposition.get_solarposition(times, 40, -80, pressure=pressure, temperature=temperature)\n",
    "        rmse = np.mean((gpu['apparent_zenith'] - cpu['apparent_zenith'])**2)**0.5\n",
    "        emax = np.max(np.abs(gpu['apparent_zenith'] - cpu['apparent_zenith']))\n",
    "        axes[i, j].scatter(cpu['apparent_zenith'], gpu['apparent_zenith'], s=1)\n",
    "        axes[i, j].axline((0, 0), slope=1, c='k')\n",
    "        axes[i, j].set_title(f'T={temperature:0.0f} $\\degree$C  P={pressure/1000:0.01f} kPa')\n",
    "        axes[i, j].text(0, 100, f'rmse={rmse:0.06f}\\nmax={emax:0.06f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(n):\n",
    "    axes[i, 0].set_ylabel('GPU')\n",
    "    axes[n-1, i].set_xlabel('CPU')\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.suptitle('Apparent Zenith')\n",
    "fig.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "16919795-93f4-43c9-9af3-fa16148aafdd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "All looks pretty good here.  Now, on to comparing calculation times!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea668f0d-298f-4ebe-967b-3c1b167f1dcf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Execution Speed Benchmarks\n",
    "\n",
    "My first-order mental model of GPU processing is that runtime is a combination of fixed costs (shader compilation, OpenGL context overhead) that are more or less constant for any input and variable costs (memory allocation, data transfer, and of course the actual algorithm runtime) that scale with the number of timestamps being simulated.  So of course it will be interesting to compare runtimes across a range of $N$, the number of simulated timestamps."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "c493d92d-62e2-423b-a3d8-7986677d2dc3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "/home/kevin/miniconda3/envs/dev/lib/python3.8/site-packages/pvlib/spa.py:991: UserWarning: The number of threads is more than the length of the time array. Only using %s threads.\n",
      "  warnings.warn('The number of threads is more than the length of '\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings('ignore', message='reloading spa')\n",
    "\n",
    "timings = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for n in 10**np.arange(1, 8):\n",
    "    times = pd.date_range('2019-01-01', freq='T', periods=n)\n",
    "    timing = {'N': n}\n",
    "\n",
    "    st = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    _ = pvlib.solarposition.spa_python(times, 40, -80, how='numpy')\n",
    "    ed = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    timing['cpu (numpy)'] = ed - st\n",
    "\n",
    "    # warmup\n",
    "    _ = pvlib.solarposition.spa_python(times[:10], 40, -80, how='numba')\n",
    "\n",
    "    st = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    _ = pvlib.solarposition.spa_python(times, 40, -80, how='numba', numthreads=4)\n",
    "    ed = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    timing['cpu (numba, 4 threads)'] = ed - st\n",
    "\n",
    "    st = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    _ = pvlib.solarposition.spa_python(times, 40, -80, how='numba', numthreads=8)\n",
    "    ed = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    timing['cpu (numba, 8 threads)'] = ed - st\n",
    "\n",
    "    st = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    _ = pvlib.solarposition.spa_python(times, 40, -80, how='numba', numthreads=16)\n",
    "    ed = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    timing['cpu (numba, 16 threads)'] = ed - st\n",
    "\n",
    "    st = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    _ = gpu_spa(times, 40, -80)\n",
    "    ed = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "    timing['gpu'] = ed - st\n",
    "\n",
    "    timings.append(timing)\n",
    "\n",
    "timings = pd.DataFrame(timings).set_index('N')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "57566541-96cd-4e7c-98b4-6279d79b30d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x600 with 2 Axes>"

     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, sharex=True, dpi=100, figsize=(6, 6))\n",
    "timings.plot(ax=axes[0], logx=True, logy=True)\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('Elapsed Time [s]')\n",
    "axes[0].grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "ratio = 1/timings.divide(timings['cpu (numpy)'], axis=0)\n",
    "ratio.plot(ax=axes[1], logx=True, logy=True)\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('Speed-up (numpy=1)')\n",
    "axes[1].grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "fig.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0c222f97-a389-4061-b718-ce35b5105279",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So, on this machine, the GPU implementation is:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Faster than the numpy implementation for all N\n",
    "- Faster than the numba implementation starting somewhere between 1000 and 10000 timestamps\n",
    "- Vastly faster (two orders of magnitude) for 100000 timestamps and beyond\n",
    "\n",
    "So for an 8760 you might expect a (20x, 3x) speedup over (numpy, numba).  For an annual 1-minute simulation (N=525600), the speedup might be (200x, 20x) over (numpy, numba).  Boggles the mind, especially considering that this GPU is a weeny integrated GPU (I think)!\n",
    "\n",
    "Here are the same timings in tabular form, for reference:"

   "source": [
    "Closing thoughts:\n",
    "\n",
    "- It's a shame that the shader compilation cost is incurred on every invocation.  I want to see if I can modify the shader in such a way that I can compile it once but apply it to an input of any length.  That would hopefully make it more competitive with numba for the smaller inputs.\n",
    "- Definitely need to fix that \"reverse Y2K bug\"...\n",
    "- Definitely want to re-run this notebook on a different computer.  I've addressed the big error sources on this machine, but the fact that the trignometric functions have such large error here gives me significant pause -- maybe other computers will have totally different error sources.  If the error is acceptable across machines (or I rewrite the code to only use \"safe\" GLSL functions), then evaluating the speed-up with a proper beefy GPU would be very cool."
   ]
  }
